{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionModel-based benchmarking, an essential engineering field used to estimate attributes such as system reliability, security, and performance, often employs Markov Chains for the probabilistic description of state-based stochastic models.",
    "While mathematically manageable, Markov Chains still necessitate efficient numerical methods to compute large-scale systems' stationary and transient metrics.",
    "When these models become non-Markovian, classical analytical approaches may prove unfeasible due to including nonexponential distributions.There are three principal methodologies when evaluating performance: analytical modeling, simulation, and measurement.",
    "Analytical modeling uses equations to predict and analyze how computational systems behave.",
    "These equations are based on understanding and estimating system behavior within a finite period and can be enhanced using Phase-type (PH) distributions."
  ]
}